{"ts":"2026-06-27T12:31:31.274Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Reviewing the Task Brief**\n\nI'm zeroing in on the specifics: I'm focusing on crafting the MVP for the documents APIs, specifically /api/v1/documents. Crucially, I'm staying clear of the landing page and any GFF AI tools. The main focus is managing metadata during this phase. I want to build the documents API.\n\n\n**Clarifying Visibility Settings**\n\nI'm now diving into the visibility field, aiming to define its behavior. I need to be exact with the visibility values. I'm considering options like \"public,\" \"restricted,\" and \"confidential,\" and how client vs admin views are different. I need to establish the visibility fields on the documents, to be clear on client access levels.\n\n\n**Defining Metadata Elements**\n\nI'm now nailing down typical metadata fields. I'm thinking about `id`, `title`, `document_type`, `status`, `version`, `owner`, `project_id`, `client_id`, and `client_name`, but I want the `visibility` field to be particularly clear. Considering \"public\", \"internal\", and \"admin_only\" for `visibility`. Need to ensure client roles can list/view documents for their `client_id` if the visibility is not for admins.\n\n\n**Refining Access Control Logic**\n\nI'm now concretizing the access control rules for different roles. Specifically, the `gff_admin` role's capabilities are clear: they can manage all documents. Client roles, on the other hand, have a key restriction. They can view/list documents only when their `client_id` matches and the document's `visibility` isn't set to \"admin_only\". I'm still debating the precise visibility values – `\"public\"` and `\"internal\"` seem sensible for client access, excluding `\"admin_only\"`.\n\n\n"}}
